018-09-19T19:54:27Z", "updated_at": "2018-10-04T18:11:08Z", "closed_at": "2018-10-04T17:40:57Z", "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR", "pull_request": {"url": "https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/pulls/22392", "html_url": "https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/22392", "diff_url": "https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/22392.diff", "patch_url": "https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/22392.patch"}, "body_html": "<p><span class=\"issue-keyword tooltipped tooltipped-se\" aria-label=\"This pull request closes issue #22190.\">Fix</span> <a class=\"issue-link js-issue-link\" data-error-text=\"Failed to load issue title\" data-id=\"358639740\" data-permission-text=\"Issue title is private\" data-url=\"https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/22190\" data-hovercard-type=\"issue\" data-hovercard-url=\"/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/22190/hovercard\" href=\"https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/22190\">#22190</a></p>\n<p>For the input of <code>tf.keras.metrics.sparse_categorical_accuracy</code>, the shape of <code>y_true</code> can be <code>(num_samples, 1)</code> or <code>(num_samples,)</code>, see <a class=\"issue-link js-issue-link\" data-error-text=\"Failed to load issue title\" data-id=\"358639740\" data-permission-text=\"Issue title is private\" data-url=\"https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/22190\" data-hovercard-type=\"issue\" data-hovercard-url=\"/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/22190/hovercard\" href=\"https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/22190\">#22190</a> for detail. The existing code assume the shape of <code>y_true</code> is <code>(num_samples, 1)</code>, always reduce in the last dimension which leads the incorrect output. Actually we should check the shape of <code>y_true</code> and squeeze if applicable.<br>\nMeanwhile, I also fix <code>sparse_top_k_categorical_accuracy</code> which has the same issue.</p>", "body_text": "Fix #22190\nFor the input of tf.keras.metrics.sparse_categorical_accuracy, the shape of y_true can be (num_samples, 1) or (num_samples,), see #22190 for detail. The existing code assume the shape of y_true is (num_samples, 1), always reduce in the last dimension which leads the incorrect output. Actually we should check the shape of y_true and squeeze if applicable.\nMeanwhile, I also fix sparse_top_k_categorical_accuracy which has the same issue.", "body": "Fix #22190\r\n\r\nFor the input of ```tf.keras.metrics.sparse_categorical_accuracy```, the shape of ```y_true``` can be ```(num_samples, 1)``` or ```(num_samples,)```, see #22190 for detail. The existing code assume the shape of ```y_true``` is ```(num_samples, 1)```, always reduce in the last dimension which leads the incorrect output. Actually we should check the shape of ```y_true``` and squeeze if applicable.\r\nMeanwhile, I also fix ```sparse_top_k_categorical_accuracy``` which has the same issue."}